  "referred_to_by": [
    {
      "type": "LinguisticObject",
      "content": "This is a marine box chronometer by Arnold & Dent, London, No. 782, dating from the partnership period of 1830–1840. It is a precision timekeeping instrument housed in a traditional three-tier mahogany box with brass gimbals, designed to maintain accurate time regardless of a ship's motion. The chronometer was acquired by Teylers Museum in 1870 as a replacement for an earlier chronometer that had worn out, and was used for astronomical observations at the museum's observatory. Edward John Dent, the junior partner, later became famous as the maker of the Great Clock of the Houses of Parliament (Big Ben).",
